Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five state travel offices approved in the then ČSSR: Čedok, athlete, CKM, recreation and car tourism.
The travel offices at that time sold mainly only travels to the socialist Eastern bloc countries, in the West only allowed selected ones at that time.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the DDR), to the Soviet Union (Sotchi on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972 when you were allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia entered a pro-western course and therefore the journeys to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed to travel freely within the socialist countries of the Eastern bloc (also the Czechoslovak).
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel to Poland individually or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, the travel offices also offered travel in the West, but they had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag before the travel office, or have at least "good acquaintances" in the travel office.
Even so, the matter has not been going on for a long time.
The so-called currency use - the condition for an exit to the West - was granted only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a free exchangeable currency, so without currency use it would have been impossible to drive the necessary funds (western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most Czechs therefore spent their vacations in the interior, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekends and desks - a habit that lasts to this day.
The entire 1989 revolution followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on foot.
Until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A powerful paradox, which you are no longer aware of today, is the fact that you could not travel in the Czech Republic's most popular holiday country until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
From the beginning of the 90s last century, the foreign currency obligation has been lifted in the neighbouring Western European countries, resulting in a huge wave of short visits mainly to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians could not get enough time from their journeys to the West, each wanted to be there for at least a few days.
This is how the Czech holidaymakers slept in the tent in the park when traveling to Paris, because who would have already had the money for a hotel accommodation or a pension.
A typical feature of travel abroad from Czech Republic was then a full-packed suitcase with cans, beer and durables, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the free exchangeable Czech krone - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living, as well as the averages, are increasing, which brought 1997 to another important point.
Due to the increased demand for travel, after 1997 travel agencies began to prepare regular trips by charter flights, thus allowing flights to negotiate quantitative discounts, which were unbelievably agreed upon in comparison with the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, already had foreign-exchange payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-office" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand for the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying every year in distant sunny countries; this year you are flying directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
To the 100 Tsd. Czechs travel in exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States raised the visa requirement for Czech tourists, so our country was definitely among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 tsd. CZK per head for a single holiday stay including the costs of the holiday.
