After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
This is easy - you only have to log in on Facebook.
"We found it not difficult to come to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the chief author of a recent report by the British Ideanfabrik DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook's hidden personal data is so encyclopaedic, Bartlett says that researchers simply need to use the advertising tool of the site to determine their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - as marketers have done for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of extreme right-wing groups across Europe and then visited them with add-ons, but instead of linking to a new band or a new diet product, Add's users invite a survey in which they were asked about their educational status, their attitude towards violence and the assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to question more than 10,000 members of 14 extremely right parties in 11 European countries - without having to leave their office even once.
"It is a rather new research method," says Bartlett.
Some of the results hardly surprise. Online advocates of right extreme groups are mostly young, male and angry about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more rational, democratic and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens."
DEMO's work is just an example of how Facebook becomes a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Ideas factories, medical researchers and politicians use the site to study everything, from health issues to social trends such as "Likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users, adding on average three content per day, Facebook's "Datasupernova" generates a research tree that has increased the number of scientific works with the name of this site in the last five years by almost 800%.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study through this page people who usually do not reach with their clipboard on the street.
"If you used to try to interview people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"They had to inform the party first and it would never have granted them access," says Bartlett.
"On Facebook it's all gone - they're going straight to them."
Others say that the site offers an opportunity to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno from the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their Facebook performance tend significantly more to drink problems than students who were talking about it.
Moreno suggests that equivalent students, such as resident advisors, monitor the site and help a student when they post too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you haven't recognized it," said Dimitri Christakis, Morenos co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, Washington Post.
"We have found an opportunity to identify dangerous children who would not have been found otherwise."
Facebook also constantly collects data from its own population.
The data team of the page has created statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, electoral participation in the 2010 elections and a national happiness index (which used first of all data that only Facebook has access to - Masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its large database available for other research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching whether they want it now or not. To be able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you allow the site to produce your own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
"I don't think many users have thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles at all," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study where he studied the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As far as she is concerned, it was just about her and her friends."
