Climate resistance inhibited the economy
In the first year, where Mario López Valdez is in the government, unemployment and black labour increased in Sinaloa, while foreign investments decreased and the economy stagnant.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloas. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who described himself as the initiator of the change and who has lost great hopes for economic growth, is in the government. However, because of the climate resistance, it cannot be the speech of growth, but rather the main economic indicators worsened.
The low temperatures in February not only resulted in losses of millions in agriculture, but also set close limits on the growth of the state economy and caused a general decrease in economic activity by 3.6 percent in the first quarter of the year. This is mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which has a brake on other sectors of the economy.
According to a report by the Council of Mexicano para el Development Rural Sustainable (i.e. the Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of the frost, 582,000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity until November has led to a continuous rise in unemployment in the Mexican state. In the first quarter of the year, the Instituto Nacional de Estadostica y Geography observed a rapid increase in unemployment, as from January to March 55,053 inhabitants of Sinaloas had no employment, corresponding to 4.53 per cent of the population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 per cent and from July to September to 6.19 per cent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa.
Less liquidity
The unemployment rate in Sinaloa in the year goes back to several factors. Economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments on the policy of public institutions declaring the growing unemployment indirectly.
"What we are currently observing is an increase in unemployment that has to do with several factors. Among other things, with liquidity losses on the market due to the cuts in funds adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for something else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has fallen. This is due to the problems of entry and to the difficulty of finding work there too. These people stay here and seek work here, which makes unemployment rise," he says.
Black work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious when considering the high proportion of black labour, which includes 60.38% of the domestic workers who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and black labour are the lowest wages in Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Agency) and the Secretariat of Labour y Prediction Social (Governmental Office for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was up to September 5352 pesos, which is much less than the total national average of 7375 pesos.
ADI decrease
In addition to the downturn in economic activity and growing unemployment, in 2011 the strongest decrease in foreign direct investment (ADI) over the last ten years has been recorded. According to the Secretariat of Economics (State Economic Authority), the ADI amounted to $630,597 from January to June, representing a shift of 87.74 per cent compared to $5,143,312 in the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Secretariat for Economic Development (Government for Economic Development) recorded a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In view of the economic crisis, in July at the National Congress, the Government applied for a loan of 3 000 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 communities. The National Congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but by November there was no positive impact of the debt on any of the economic sectors in the country.
Reactions
For the representatives of the company, the first year of government, Mario López Valdé's inability to govern was evident.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of the Processing Industry in Mexico) said that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the national government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very good this year. It has to be worked hard to recover the land lost this year and in 2012 we have to double our effort. The efforts of all and, in particular, the progress of the already well-agreed government teams have not been sufficiently matched," he said.
Long-term economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year aggravated and slowed the economic development of the country.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important effects is a slow economy that is not moving enough to produce an economic dynamic that could produce an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. That is why we will complete the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefine the call
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confedéración Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexican Association of Enterprises) in Sinaloa, stated that the state had to be set up for more dynamic productive activities.
"In general we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme to redefine the country's economic vocation and line, because it is important to activate all material and human resources Sinaloas," he said.
There's a lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will drive the government's efforts on better roads.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power has made progress with the government.
"There are areas where you can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that it has been worked and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
