Asphalt from UNAM prevents shock holes
Rafael Herrera, Researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico UNAM develops modified asphalts with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs from the road cover were to be taken into account, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 impact holes when the rainy season in the Metropolitana del Valle de México area (city of the valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, cautioning and ensuring that if the discharge and maintenance of the ash cover are appropriate, the number of impact holes will be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his presentation "Technical blowholes", which he held on occasion during the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, which however has a greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Mr Nájera thought that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and to avoid striking holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heavy part of the oil - is a hydrogen compound, some of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthene. Together, they give the street cover its characteristic numerical behavior.
The analytical behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves at high temperatures of almost 180°C as a liquid, at 120°C it is very liquid and it is almost fixed at 50°C while it breaks at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the streets is not the same, but one day it changes depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer said.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City had mostly a flexible road cover consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which contained asphalt.
Among the top layers is a layer of asphalt, which consists of small, asphalt-bathed and then solidified stones.
Each single stone of this wear layer has been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move forward and forces are generated, this layer enables a good distribution of power in the road cover.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemical engineer.
"On the wear layer," he explained, "a final layer is made up of so-called wear layer consisting of small stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they need to produce friction.
This road cover receives and distributes most of the forces and also needs a proper thickness and the material from which it is made must be maintained.
The weather conditions, particularly humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially water," he said, "because it affects the wear layer behaviour significantly.
When the ground is wet, water enters the layer and only becomes difficult again. This causes a diversion of all layers of the road surface and consequently the appearance of impact holes.
When a blow hole arises," he said, "the cover layer will be removed first, while the wear layer will only be affected afterwards. However, the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained during the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
