North Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is expected to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted this event to take place with splendor and glory.
Over 500 loaded guests, including four Heads of State and Government, have been living on the Baltic Sea Coast last Tuesday under orchestral noise and at fine-sweet buffet the opening of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea level.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedew, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his colleague Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically combined the control of the valve, which transports Russian gas to the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, additional Russian gases of 27.5 billion cubic metres per year are to be delivered to Western Europe by a first pipeline of 1.224 km long, connecting the region of St. Petersburg with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline that allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - equivalent to French total consumption - is to be completed at the end of 2012.
And you can already anchor the possibility of building a third line on the same track.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this huge construction works is like a victory.
The project was strongly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The North Stream pipeline will allow direct gas delivery to Germany, while avoiding any passage through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on the road.
This is why these two countries are losing a little of their power: it will now be more difficult for them to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to shut down access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most strongly engaged in the debate, was not reluctant to compare the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
This, however, is at the expense of strengthening European energy, as the project has struck a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
Russia has almost five years to complete its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, western countries with strong gas consumption and fluctuating their gas emissions.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," said François Fillon in the opening of the gas pipeline, pointing to the extent to which the major gas contracts are also important from a political and economic point of view.
All of this explains the broad smile of the gasprom manager represented in Lubmin regarding the gas pipeline.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an excellent technique.
The underwater line consists of steel with concrete coating to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the sea floor, in about 200 m deep.
In its construction, mine fields dating from World War II had to be balanced.
"Approximately a hundred mines had to be carefully removed or destroyed," said Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased catches were required to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long tube of metal, hard like 242 eiffel Towers, which is interrupted over the entire length by nothing: neither by valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in front of the coast of Sweden, but the project managers took a distance from it, as the Swedes were not aware of the fact that a Russian state company would sit permanently at the height of its coasts.
"In case of an accident, we close the gas pass in less than one minute," Jens Müller said.
In the case of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered by the constructors as only unlikely, as the swivel knots were estimated to be resistant to a leak per 100,000 years.
The State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured by both an underwater robot, which is controlled for external observation by a marine vessel, as well as by a device operating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigarette, weighs a meter diameter, is introduced into the inside of the pipeline and moved by the gas pressure.
After three complete days of movement through the wire at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on any deformation of the metal upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to undergo only the smallest repair.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have united their forces to carry out this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E.ON and BASF are included here (up to 15.5%), as well as the Dutch gas union and the French company group GDF Suez (up to 9%).
These five companies have formed a company community called Nord Stream, which is commissioned with the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It has its seat in train in Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
